eaching Older Generations through Adult Education Programs And Appendix: Archaeological Heritage Survey 2015 -- tPart III. The Future of Archaeology, Education, and Preservation -- tChapter 8. Best Practices in Archaeology Education: Successes, Shortcomings, and the Future -- tChapter 9. Navigating Heritage Stewardship in the Digital Age -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world’s collective archaeological heritage is threatened by war, development, poverty, climate change, and ignorance. To protect our collective past, archaeologists must involve the general public through interpersonal experiences that develop an interest in the field at a young age and foster that interest throughout a person’s life. Contributors to this volume share effective approaches for engaging and educating learners of all ages about archaeology and how one can encourage them to become stewards of the past. They offer applied examples that are not bound to specific geographies or cultures, but rather, are approaches that can be implemented almost anywhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArchaeologyxStudy and teaching. 0aCommunity archaeology. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aArchaeological Heritage, Education, Public Archaeology, Civic Engagement, Participation.1 aAbdella, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbrecht, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreager, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDucady, Geralyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllison, Leigh Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela